body:
Probably there is a related issue somewhere tracking the remaining work for 1.12  , but I haven't found it,
and with a new issue it will be just lost among the open ones, so:
The new python3.10 support implies that the setup.py classifiers should be updated, and 
` "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.10" `
should be added both to master and to the 1.12 release branch.
These tags are used by Pypi.org, e.g. to show supported version. 
Similarly, 3.6 should be removed, because only 3.7+ is supported.

@dvolgyes 
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/12141

Using ðŸ¤— [Optimum](https://github.com/huggingface/optimum/) to optimize a model for GPU and load an ORT inference session using TensorrtExecutionProvider results in the following error

```bash
ort.InferenceSession("./artifacts/model-optimized.onnx", providers=["TensorrtExecutionProvider"])
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
  File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/onnxruntime/capi/onnxruntime_inference_collection.py", line 347, in __init__
    self._create_inference_session(providers, provider_options, disabled_optimizers)
  File "/usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/onnxruntime/capi/onnxruntime_inference_collection.py", line 395, in _create_inference_session
    sess.initialize_session(providers, provider_options, disabled_optimizers)
RuntimeError: /onnxruntime_src/onnxruntime/core/session/provider_bridge_ort.cc:1025 onnxruntime::Provider& onnxruntime::ProviderLibrary::Get() [ONNXRuntimeError] : 1 : FAIL : Failed to load library libonnxruntime_providers_tensorrt.so with error: /usr/local/lib/python3.8/dist-packages/onnxruntime/capi/libonnxruntime_providers_tensorrt.so: undefined symbol: getBuilderPluginRegistry
```

For more background on this please see the following issues [274](https://github.com/huggingface/optimum/issues/274) and [288](https://github.com/huggingface/optimum/issues/288).

Steps to reproduce:

1. Run `nvcr.io/nvidia/tensorrt:22.06-py3` container on GPU machine
2. Install onnxruntime-gpu from 1.12.0 RC
```bash
pip install -i https://test.pypi.org/simple/ ort-nightly-gpu==1.12.0.dev20220707003
```
3. Install other deps
```bash
pip install transformers datasets onnx optimum
```
4. Export ðŸ¤— model to ONNX optimized for GPU with the following script
```python
from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForCausalLM
from optimum.onnxruntime.configuration import OptimizationConfig
from optimum.onnxruntime import ORTModelForCausalLM, ORTOptimizer


model = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained('distilgpt2')
tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained('distilgpt2', padding=True, truncation=True)

optimization_config = OptimizationConfig(optimization_level=99, optimize_for_gpu=True)
optimizer = ORTOptimizer(
    model=model, preprocessor=tokenizer, feature="causal-lm", opset=13,
)
optimizer.export(
    onnx_model_path="model.onnx",
    onnx_optimized_model_output_path="model-optimized.onnx",
    optimization_config=optimization_config,
    use_external_data_format=True,
)
```
5. Try to load model using TensorrtExecutionProvider
```python
optimized_model = ORTModelForCausalLM.load_model("./model-optimized.onnx", provider="TensorrtExecutionProvider")
```
6. (Optional) Try to load model directly with ORT
```python
import onnxruntime as ort


ort.InferenceSession("./model-optimized.onnx", providers=["TensorrtExecutionProvider"])
```

### UPDATE
This Docker image actually comes with TensorRT 8.2 pip package installed. After upgrading to 8.4.1.5 I get

Please run shape inference on the onnx model first. Details can be found in https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/execution-providers/TensorRT-ExecutionProvider.html#shape-inference-for-tensorrt-subgraphs

Upon trying to run the suggested script I get

```bash
  File "symbolic_shape_infer.py", line 2424, in <module>
    out_mp = SymbolicShapeInference.infer_shapes(
  File "symbolic_shape_infer.py", line 2360, in infer_shapes

Exception: Incomplete symbolic shape inference
```

I tested out the CPU one on macOS x86_64, and everything works fine. I had to add this snippet (which is given in the link but I'm repeating to help anyone else interested) to Tribuo's Maven build file and then modify the version number we pull in, but that was it.

``` 
   <repositories>
    <repository>
      <id>ORT-Nightly</id>
      <url>https://aiinfra.pkgs.visualstudio.com/PublicPackages/_packaging/ORT-Nightly/maven/v1</url>
      <releases>
        <enabled>true</enabled>
      </releases>
      <snapshots>
        <enabled>true</enabled>
      </snapshots>
  </repository>
  </repositories>
```

The name & version is a bit problematic though as Maven expects there to be only ever one artifact named by a group id, artifact id and version tuple, so testing out that one will mean people cache it locally in preference to downloading the real `v1.12.0` when it is released. Maybe it should have `v1.12.0-rc1` as the version number?
